                                                                                                               IL amp;FS set to take control of Maytas
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Khurshid: Strategic decision                                  
	New Delhi, Aug. 31: Infrastructure major IL amp;FS, which is set to take management control of Maytas Infra, will invest Rs 55 crore over the next three months to revive the cash-strapped firm. The company will acquire an additional 22.51 per cent stake in Maytas to take its holding to 37.1 per cent.        
	IL amp;FS will be the new owner of Maytas Infra with immediate effect, controlling 37.1 per cent in the company, Salman Khurshid, the company affairs minister, said.        
	ICICI Bank, IDBI Bank and the State Bank of India  key lenders to Maytas  had invited IL amp;FS to take a strategic role in the revival of the company, the infrastructure firm said in a statement.        
	IL amp;FS, which is the single largest shareholder of Maytas, currently holds 14.5 per cent in the company. Of its total equity of 37.1 per cent in Maytas, 22.6 per cent will be from shares pledged to it by the original promoters.        
	IL amp;FS shall, for a period of not less than two years, hold a minimum 26 per cent in the company and keep management control during that period. It will also be required to infuse up to Rs 55 crore as liquidity support, according to an order by the Company Law Board (CLB).        
	The CLB has also allowed IL amp;FS to appoint four directors, including the chairman, on the Maytas board. Two of the four government-appointed directors will stay on the board till September 2010. The names will be finalised shortly, said Khurshid.        
	Maytas was founded by the family of Ramalinga Raju, the former chairman of Satyam Computer Services, who confessed in January to an accounting fraud in the IT firm. Following Rajus disclosures, the government had appointed K. Ramalingam as chairman of Maytas. .P. Vaish, Ved Jain and Anil K. Agarwal were the other new directors.        
	B. Teja Raju, vice-chairman of the company and Ramalinga Rajus son, and whole-time director B. Narasimha Rao will step down with immediate effect, Khurshid said.        
	The IL amp;FS and Maytas boards will meet tomorrow in Hyderabad to discuss the modalities of the takeover. A date for an open offer will also be decided. IL amp;FS has to go for an open offer to acquire another 20 per cent in Maytas.                                                                                                                                        
